commentBody:
@Newbie 

Well, at least emu is almost just like emo (hello, My Chemical Romance). 

LOLA was a good catch. I missed it, and I read through the clues and answers twice after finishing.

@Al  in Pittsburgh 

I was just reading your notes, laughing at your showcasing of Sly’s “I’ll pheeze”—I remember looking that up. I was going to say that I was sure I had looked it up when I labored my way through Shakespeare the first time around many moons ago but clearly hadn’t committed it to memory—but actually, no, I’m not sure of that at all. Taking OED tomes off the shelves back then was not as easy as long press & select “look up.” 

Kids have Shakespeare easy these day [grin].

@Joy M. 

Glad to read all your parts are aligned!

😉

@Newbie 
Oh no, the fill wasn't 'easy' at all.  At first it looked hopeless.  But as I worked on it, gradually one corner fell, and then another...  Checking my Wednesday stats, I see my time was somewhere between 'best' and 'average', so not the slowest...

I do agree the reveal was inspired, though.

@Eric Hougland 

Wow, that's cool. 

I would be so dead if that were the first car I drove... For me it was a Daewoo Lanos, and the only thing it had in common with the Firebird was stick shift (5 speed in this case. Practically no car in Poland was an automatic well into the 2000s). It had a 1,6 liter 106 BHP engine and I drove it like a madman. I have no idea how I survived - by pure chance I guess. I am very ashamed of what an idiot I was back then, at 20 (legal age for drivers is 18 here, but I had no time to take the course and exam before I turned 20. Getting into law school was quite a time-consuming effort). These days I drive much faster cars but I do it very slowly.

@Steve L 

IIRC, "decalcomania," or something very similar. I recall this from my plastic model-building days, 60 years ago, give or take.

(I miss building models. Thought about picking it up again as a hobby, but between arthritis and the price of models . . . )

@Randolph 

I've had a similar experience, on my MacBook. Started puzzle at home, went to basement pub (no wifi) and finished puzzle, when I got home it had no record of my finished puzzle; it was completed to the point of when I'd left home.

I think if my internet connection is interrupted/spotty, odd things happen to my puzzles and times. (For example, stats say my fastest Friday is 3:15 which is ludicrous.)

@jma 
